1 Philosophy

This document serves as a basis for “efficient working with R” and gives recommendations to make data analysis with R easier, more efficient, consistent and reproducible:

  • Standard definition for structuring files to make it easier to find stuff again (others as well as “future-you”)
  • Keep things together, which belong together by content.
  • Consistent work with R (templates and coding standard)
  • Make data analysis with R reproducible
  • Share tips and tricks for working with R(studio)

Note that exceptions are always OK, if there are good reasons for.

2 Project structure

We strongly recommend to use the existing project structure of the “Schwarzes Brett” for all projects since folders are accessible to all project collaborators. The JR-POL project folder contains all organizational, legally and economically relevant documents and notes, from which the current status and progress of a project is recognisable. The project leader is responsible for the preparation and processing of the project folder. For details, see the QM-Handbuch, Ablage von Projektunterlagen.

2.1 Working directory: folders & files

The structure of the working directory and its corresponding folder content are described below.

##    levelName                wd_name
## 1  "root"                   NA     
## 2   ¦--01_data              NA     
## 3   ¦   ¦--01_original      NA     
## 4   ¦   °--02_work          NA     
## 5   ¦--02_work              NA     
## 6   ¦   °--R_projname       NA     
## 7   ¦--03_results           NA     
## 8   ¦   ¦--01_output        NA     
## 9   ¦   ¦   °--tmp          NA     
## 10  ¦   ¦--02_reports       NA     
## 11  ¦   °--03_presentations NA     
## 12  ¦--04_literature        NA     
## 13  °--05_other             NA

Note that this structure is always expandable specific to a project, i.e., subfolders for additionally structuring your files are possible in all directories.

01_data/
  • 01_original
  • 02_work

This folder contains all data that are used in a project. Original (read only!) data are stored in the subfolder 01_original and should not be modified in any way. Processed/edited data (e.g., prepared data and .rds files, generated in R, Excel etc.) are stored in the subfolder 02_work.

02_work/
  • R_projname

In a nutshell, this folder holds all “work files”. It contains the R-project directory R_projname (where projname is the (short) name of the corresponding project) which includes your .Rproj-file, all R code and further R-related files such as your .Rprofile-file and several templates which are described below. See section How to start for details on creating a new Rstudio-project.

We suggest to use the same structure when using other software such as SAS or SPSS (e.g., SAS_projname).

We further recommend to use a consistent workflow when working with R (or a comparible) software. This workflow involves

  • an initialization file for your project (00_init.R) to specify working directories, required packages and general settings
  • a file which collects all functions which are used within a project (00_functions.R)
  • (separate) data preparation files (e.g., 01_data_prep.R) to prepare your data prior to analysis (do not mix data preparation steps with code to analyse your data)
  • data analysis files (e.g., 02_data_analysis.R)

Note that it is recommended to prefix file names with numbers for structuring R (or SAS) file names. The (consecutive) numbering is project specific and arbitrary.

03_results/
  • 01_output/tmp
  • 02_reports
  • 03_presentations

This folder holds all project results. In detail, 01_output contains figures and tables (e.g., csv-files genereated in R) where the additional subfolder tmp can be used to store temporary results. Subfolders (e.g. to save figures and tables separately) can be created for reasons of clarity, depending on a project extent.
All reports (i.e., progress reports, final reports) are saved in the subfolder 02_reports. We suggest to clearly identify the (very last) version of the final report by adding the supplemenet “_final” (e.g., “xxx_final.docx” or “xxx_final.pdf”) to the document name.
As the name suggests, presentation slides (such as .ppt or .pdf files) are stored in the folder 03_presentations. Again, the final version of the slides should be highlighted by the supplement “_final” in the document name.

04_literature/
All sources of literature used within a project are stored in the folder 04_literatrue.

05_other/
This folder contains all project work (!) related documents which do not fit into the previous project folders.

2.2 Templates

For working with R within a project several templates are provided to make data analysis with R easier, more consistent and more reproducible. It is also intended to stop the working directory insanity.

An important part of the concept are working directories, which are defined in 00_init.R. There are two important directories:

  1. The R-project directory wd_rproj: This is the directory holding your .Rproj-file and your .Rprofile-file. Typically also your code lies here. Subfolders for structuring your files are allowed. The path will be auto-generated.
  2. The project directory wd_proj: This is the directory, where the above defined folder structure is expected. Thus wd_rproj is typically a subfolder. In any case, everything except R-code is expected corresponding to the above folder structure. wd_proj is tried to be auto-generated from the R-project directory.

When you want your R-code in a different place from the project folder, you may use the project_directory option of the project.yaml-file (see below).

.Rprofile

  • Initialization file of the R-session being sourced when starting R
  • 00_init.R will be sourced, if it exists
  • The project directory is searched and set.
  • It creates and appends a sessionInfo.log file at the end of your Rstudio-session.
  • Usually you only need to take care to not to remove it.
  • You can also manually use the template-infrastructure by source(".Rprofile"); .First().

00_init.R

  • Initialization file for your project
  • This file is designed to being sourced at project start. Here everything can be defined, that should be globally available for your project. The following is suggested:
    • Define all working directories as variables starting with wd_ (hint: use file.path() to specify working directories/paths to load and save files!)
    • Load all needed R packages.
    • Source all function-files here.
    • Define here general settings, variables or similar code, which will be available for all other files.
    • Do not insert code which takes considerable time, as this file is loaded on each project startup.

00_functions.R

  • File that contains all functions of your project
  • If you feel to have too many functions for one file, you might of course create multiple function-files or even create a folder for your function files.

project.yaml

  • Metafile according to the yaml-format with project information
  • The following entries are currently defined:
    • project_yaml_version: the version of the yaml-file (do not modify!)
    • project_directory: optional parameter to set the project directory. The following values are allowed:
      • NULL, NA or empty: the project directory is dynamically generated based on the location of your code
      • a path: if a path is specified, this is taken as the project directory. You do this typically, if your project lies on a network drive, while your code is local. This is recommended, when collaborating with git.
    • load_init: TRUE or FALSE indicating, if the init-file should automatically be loaded on startup of the Rstudio-project
    • load_files: allows to define additional files to be loaded at project startup (order is considered)
    • title: Title of the project
    • authors: Author or authors of the project
    • R_version: expected R-version

The template structure will create and append a sessionInfo.log file at the end of your Rstudio-session. It records your R-session-info and your user information. This is for you to recapture what might have happened if something goes wrong. Usually you don’t need to track this file with git.

2.3 How to start

Working with Rstudio-projects is strongly recommended. For creating a new Rstudio-project, please do the following:

  1. You need to have some packages installed, to use all features. The following code tests for those packages and installs them, if needed:
if (!require("yaml")) install.packages("yaml")
if (!require("tidyverse")) install.packages("tidyverse")
if (!require("rmarkdown")) install.packages("rmarkdown")
if (!require("praise")) install.packages("praise")
if (!require("data.tree")) install.packages("data.tree")
if (!require("rprojroot")) install.packages("rprojroot")
if (!require("devtools")) install.packages("devtools")
  1. Copy the folder structure (working directory including templates) stored in /.../07 Projekte/_R-Struktur_Musterordner/ (Schwarzes Brett) to your desired destination (network drive project folders are recommended).
  2. Rename the folder 02_work/R_projname by replacing projname with the (short) name of your project (lower case, separated by “_“, no special characters).
  3. Open the project.yaml-file and edit it according to your project.
  4. Open Rstudio.
  5. File -> New Project -> Existing Directory
  6. Set the project directory to the folder renamed in step 3. Press “Create Project”.

2.3.1 Collaborating

By default, the project assumes that all your relevant files are within the project directory you are currently in. For collaborating in projects, we recommend placing the project files on a shared directory (in our case: “pol_sb”). So please follow the following steps:

  1. Create the project structure and the Rstudio project as described above.
  2. Set the project directory (directory containing folder templates) in the project.yaml-file.
    Remark: If the project directory is on a network drive, be sure to use the network-path NOT containting an associated drive letter.
  3. Make your project a git project (see here).
  4. For each person wanting to collaborate with, get a git-project copy (see here).
    Remarks: Typically you want your git-project copy locally. You may also want to use the project structure to put your git-project copy into, although this is not needed.

Remember the following:

  • You are working on a private copy of the files tracked with git.
  • The data is loaded from the common project files (as specified in project.yaml) which is typically not local (!) but on the shared pol_sb directory. So you usally do not need any data to be stored locally.
  • The results are saved in the common project folders.

2.4 Naming: Folders & files

We suggest to consider the following recommendations which (may) serve as a general guideline in structuring folder and file naming conventions to be consistent and descriptive in naming and organizing:

  • Keep file and folder names short, but meaningful.
  • English is the default language for naming folders and files. If one uses German, we strongly recommend to avoid Umlauts, especially for folder names. In any case, do not use special characters or whitespaces and stick to [a-z], [A-Z], [0-9], [_,-].
  • Use lower case letters.
  • Do not use “.” but the underscore “_” as element delimiter. Additionally, consider the following suggestions for folders and files:
Folders
  • Prefix folders (and subfolders) with numbers for structuring, i.e., use “00_name” (exception: “02_work/R_projname”, etc.).
  • Avoid long folder names. The maximum path length is 260. For details, see here.
  • Do not use Umlauts (in project paths)!
Files
  • Prefix files with numbers for structuring, i.e., use “00_name” (exception: README, meta files, etc.).
  • Order the elements in a file name in the most appropriate way to retrieve the record, e.g., include the current date in the file name if there are several versions of the same document.

2.5 Special cases

When working and collaborating with the above defined project structure you may encounter special cases not covered so far. Therefore we tried to identify the most relevant special cases together with solutions:

2.5.1 Working outside the company network

It might happen, that you need to access your project from outside the company network (e.g. at a costumer). One option is to use VPN (provided by Rechenzentrum), but this is slow. VPN also does not work without internet. We identified some solutions for these situations:

  • Offline access (recommended): The company Windows versions should be equipped with the tool “Synchronisierugnscenter”. It let’s you define folders on shared drives which should be available offline. Windows saves the files on your local drive and syncs whenever your connected to the network. See here (german) for some details.
    This approach let’s you access all your project files anytime and anywhere.
    Remark: Please be aware that all offline available data needs local storage. So periodic relesae of offline access for not further needed data is recommeded. You can release offline versions via (german): “Synchoronisierungscenter” -> “Offlinedateien verwalten” -> “Offlinedateien anzeigen” -> Browse to to a folder to release -> right click -> “Offlinekopie löschen”
  • Brute force copy: A very simple and robust way is to copy the whole folder structure (or at least all needed files) to your local drive. Of course you might need to adapt your project path.
    The main drawback of this approach is that you have to move all relevant changes back to the network drive by yourself which might be time-consuming, especially in case of large data sets.
  • Saving the R workspace: This issue might be easier in the special case where you only want to access R code and some results within R. A prerequisite for this approach is that you have your code local (e.g. as via git-collaboration). In this case you can load all relevant objects into the R workspace while connected to the network drive and save the workspace locally as RDA-file. This makes it possible to load the RDA-file offline and work with it. Of course, you do not have access to all network-project-folders (e.g. the results-folder) via this approach.

2.5.2 Splitting a project

Sometimes it is needed to split a project into different parts with separate R-projects. We recommend to choose one of the following two options depending on the specific project:

  1. Multiple R(studio)-projects: If you need multiple R(studio)-projects which can share the same projects structure (e.g. data or results-folder), then this might be your way. Just create multiple R-project folders within the 02_work/-folder. Each can be treated separately in a standard way as already described. Just pay attention that the projects might use the same project structure. So changes affect both R-projects.
  2. Multiple project structures: If your project-subtasks are too independent, so that you want them to have different project-folder-structures, then this approach might suit to you. Wherever your project-folders and -files are stored, just create two folder structures side by side (with speaking names). The standard approach would be to create two folders within the 05 Arbeitsverzeichnis folder side by side containing independent folder structures as described above.
    This approach makes it possible to separate data, results and all other work-related documents.

2.5.3 Not working on default shared drive

For some reason, you might want/need to place your project files somewhere else than on the default shared drive (in our case “pol_sb”). In this case, we recommend leaving a file explaining your reasons and the location of your project files in 05 Arbeitsverzeichnis. This should be accompanied by a shortcut to this location.

In any case, we recommend using some shared drive as your alternative location, as this makes collaboration and secure backups possible. For special needs, the Rechenzentrum is your friend :).

2.5.4 Working on R-Server

Luckily, we have an R-server (http://polv301.joanneum.at:8787) for doing calculations not on your personal computer. Unfortunately, it is not straight-forward to use the R-server along with our presented project structure. This is the case as we decided to keep the data as well as the results on our dedicated project-network-drive “pol_sb”. The issue is that it is difficult to access “pol_sb” from the R-server.

Our first-help approach would be to place your project structure on the R-server by following the “Not working on default shared drive” recommendation. This should make the rest of our concept work properly. The reason is that it is possible to access the R-server and it’s file system from your computer.

If you want to use this approach, please let us know, so that we can check out if it is possible to develop a standardized approach for all of us.

2.5.5 Missing “01_admin”?

Some people might be used to a folder named 01_admin in their project folder. This folder was omitted since administrative and organisational files should go to the corresponding folders defined by our QM-system (see here). Instead, we created the folder 05_other for all files not fitting in any other place. If you still miss 01_admin or need it for any other reason, we recommend creating a folder 00_admin but keep in mind that other persons (including future-you) need to find the files you created.

2.5.6 Using another programming language?

R is great and you can do nearly everything needed with R. If you do not know R well, learn it 🎓 (see section “Learn, learn, learn”). If you need/want to use another programming language, it’s easy to integrate it in our project structure. Just create a separate folder within 02_work/ containing your code as described before.

3 File versioning / git

Use Git-Versioning for the whole project folder. A .gitignore-template is provided to give a standard definition for ignoring files, which should not be versioned.

3.1 What is version control?

Here’s a short video introduction:

3.2 Why version control?

Version control in general and especially git are nowadays standard tools for data science and statistics. Git is strongly recommended by many R professionals, as it makes working with code professional. The reason is that git helps you tracking your code, saving versions of your code, it makes collaboration easier and lets future-you know what you have done in the past. Furthermore, git is one of the core tools helping to make research reproducible (see section about reproducibility).

More reasons why to use git?

  • Read a blog post about Why you need version control.
  • Git is free and open source.
  • The popular open source hosting website Github strongly bases on git.

3.3 How to start

Beside Rstudio-projects, working with git (a version control system) is strongly recommended. When working with git, a remote repository helps keeping track as well as sharing code. As JR-internal repository we use Gitea.

There are two variants for starting to work with git and Gitea:

3.3.1 Create your own git-project

To make your Rstudio-project a git-project (git needs to be installed and set up) do the following:

  1. Rstudio menu bar -> Tools
  2. Project Options
  3. Git/SVN
  4. Version control system
  5. Choose “Git”
  6. Make your first commit via Rstudio

For using Gitea do the following:

  1. Create a new project on Gitea. Press “New Repository” and set project name to R_projname.
  2. Open the shell from within Rstudio (tab Git -> gear-wheel (More) -> New Terminal).
  3. Execute git remote add origin <ssh_url_to_your_repo> (copy from Gitea) (right mouse key -> Edit -> Insert).
  4. If not yet done: Make your first commit via Rstudio.
  5. Return to the terminal and execute git push -u origin master which “pushes” your first commit.

3.3.2 Get a git-project someone else created

  1. Open Rstudio -> File -> New Project
  2. Version Control -> Git
  3. Paste the repository url (e.g., from Gitlab or Github or Gitea).
  4. Browse to the folder, where the folder for the git-project should be stored.
  5. Press “Create Project”.

3.3.3 Issues regarding network paths

On using git from Rstudio on Windows there are some issues regarding network paths Especially when opening an Rstudio project from a network path without an associated drive letter, you won’t be able to use git from withon Rstudio. So please consider:

  • Open Rstudio projects located on a network drive from a path using an assciated drive letter (e.g. "H:/07 Projekte/...").
  • For setting network paths as project directories in the project.yaml-file, please use the path NOT containging the assciated drive letter (e.g. "//rzjna01/pol_sb/07 Projekte/...").

  • Use meaningful commit messages.
  • Comment related changes.
  • Commit often.
  • Version control is not a backup system.
  • Agree on a (consistent) workflow with your collaborators.
  • Sourcetree is a great visual tool helping you to grasp what happens. People also speak very positively about GitKraken
  • There are many great resources out there to help you working with git. Here are some selected:

  • Sophisticated users may also use branching. If you want to learn about branching, here’s a great learning resource. There are different concepts for branching, which are linked here:

4 Efficient data analyis with R(Studio)

Efficient data analysis in our view is much about writing “good” code. It also means using tools (e.g. Rstudio and git) to help you manage your code. The goal is to enhance the process of producing high quality code (with focus on quality). Plus: it’s more fun 😋. In your opinion one important point is reproducibility. It means that your results should be reproducible by you, other people and future-you.

This section covers many tips and tricks about several aspects of coding especially with . Some are more general and some are very specific. Sometimes the also overlap, but this might help you to remined them 😉. In any case we strongly recommend to also read the general recommendations (e.g. Writing “good” code) and to consider them while coding.

By the way: The Coding Standard will help you on the way to efficient data analysis.

4.1 Writing “good” code

The following principles give some general outline on how to write “good code (source: David Smith):

  • Transparency: Logical organisation of units
    • Structures and organizes your code and your project in general.
    • Structure may need some time to start, but it will pay of. It will be easier for others to collaborate or work with your code as well as for yourself (present-you and future-you).
  • Maintainability: Standardization, clear comments
    • Comment about why you do what.
  • Modularity: DRY (don’t repeat yourself) Principle, Discrete units
    • Put global variables for your project on 00_init.R.
    • Write functions for repeated tasks.
    • Write functions for single tasks (if a function does multiple things, think about splitting it).
    • When you happen to change the same thing in your code on different places, think about writing a function covering the task.
  • Portability: Relative paths, minimize dependencies, dependencies are clear
    • Make code files as independent as possible.
    • Document dependencies (between files, software versions, etc.).
  • Reproducibility: Easy to reproduce results
    • see section Reproducibility
  • Efficiency: Easy to maintain and modify

4.1.1 Writing “good” R-code

Additionally here are some more specific tipps regarding writing “good” code with :

  • Treat original data as read-only.
  • You should be able to reproduce all of your analysis and your saved files only by using the data and your code.
  • Save intermediate results. If file A depends on results from another file B, save the needed results of file A within file A and load them at the beginning of file B.
  • Document how your files depend on each others results in your README-file.
  • Do not use attach() (it makes variable usage intransparent).
  • Do not save your current environment in an .Rdata-file! Always start your project with an empty environment.
  • Design files for being sourced:
    • All relevant data within the file should be loaded at the beginning of the file (or at least within the file). The file should not depend on any other variables (except for variables from 00_init.R).
    • All relevant output should be saved at the end (or at least within) the file.
  • Use set.seed() when doing non-deterministic operations.
  • Use stringsAsFactors = FALSE
  • Use RDS files instead of RDA files.
  • Paths
    • Use file.path() (not paste()) to create paths
    • Use relative paths or at least build your paths relative to a single absolute path.

4.1.2 Best Practices for Scientific Computing

To write “good” data anylsis code, there’s a lot to learn from computer science. Here are some best practices for good scientifc computing (source):

  1. Write programs for people, not computers.
    1. A program should not require its readers to hold more than a handful of facts in memory at once.
    2. Make names consistent, distinctive, and meaningful.
    3. Make code style and formatting consistent.
  2. Let the computer do the work.
    1. Make the computer repeat tasks.
    2. Save recent commands in a file for re-use.
    3. Use a build tool to automate workflows.
  3. Make incremental changes.
    1. Work in small steps with frequent feedback and course correction.
    2. Use a version control system.
    3. Put everything that has been created manually in version control.
  4. Don’t repeat yourself (or others).
    1. Every piece of data must have a single authoritative representation in the system.
    2. Modularize code rather than copying and pasting.
    3. Re-use code instead of rewriting it.
  5. Plan for mistakes.
    1. Add assertions to programs to check their operation.
    2. Use an off-the-shelf unit testing library.
    3. Turn bugs into test cases.
    4. Use a symbolic debugger.
  6. Optimize software only after it works correctly.
    1. Use a profiler to identify bottlenecks.
    2. Write code in the highest-level language possible.
  7. Document design and purpose, not mechanics.
    1. Document interfaces and reasons, not implementations.
    2. Refactor code in preference to explaining how it works.
    3. Embed the documentation for a piece of software in that software.
  8. Collaborate.
    1. Use pre-merge code reviews.
    2. Use pair programming when bringing someone new up to speed and when tackling particularly tricky problems.
    3. Use an issue tracking tool.

4.2 Reproducibility

Why reproducibility?

(… because non-reproducibility is a nightmare)

Read about reproducibility:

  • Reproducible Research with R and Rstudio (available for download here)
  • CRAN Task View on Reproducible Research
  • Reproducibility Guide by ROpenSci

4.2.1 Ten Simple Rules for Reproducible Computational Research

To be more general here are ten Simple Rules for Reproducible Computational Research (source):

  • Rule 1: For Every Result, Keep Track of How It Was Produced
  • Rule 2: Avoid Manual Data Manipulation Steps
  • Rule 3: Archive the Exact Versions of All External Programs Used
  • Rule 4: Version Control All Custom Scripts
  • Rule 5: Record All Intermediate Results, When Possible in Standardized Formats
  • Rule 6: For Analyses That Include Randomness, Note Underlying Random Seeds
  • Rule 7: Always Store Raw Data behind Plots
  • Rule 8: Generate Hierarchical Analysis Output, Allowing Layers of Increasing Detail to Be Inspected
  • Rule 9: Connect Textual Statements to Underlying Results
  • Rule 10: Provide Public Access to Scripts, Runs, and Results

4.3 Reading and writing files

Reading and writing files is essential for analysing data, as it links your code to your data as well as to your results. We think that this connection should be made clear and reproducible by your code. Here are some practical tips to

  • Use file.path() to generate paths to directories and files (instead of paste())
  • Treat raw data as read only (!). Save modified data extra.
  • Save different steps of your data analysis. For example, save data at the end of files and read it again in other files. This helps separating your code and makes scripts more independent (see also “Design files for being sourced” above).
  • Try to standardize your file format usage. Our recommendations are:
    • For code (and all other types of text files) use UTF-8 encoding.
    • Save your plots and graphics ans PNG (portable network graphic), which is usually good for web as well as reports and other documents.
    • If using csv, choose one format to stick with within a project. We recommend to either use
      • read.csv or read.csv2 (or from the readr-package read_csv and read_csv2) for reading as well as
      • write.csv or write.csv2 (or from the readr-package write_csv and coming soon write_csv2) for writing.

4.4.1 General tips and tricks

RStudio is in general a very flexible tool offering a lot of tools to support programming. You probably know some tools like code completion, the package manager, the build in help, the environment pane and so on. If you’re interested in the basics, please have a look at:

Here we’ll focus on how Rstudio can help you working with code. The main starting point for this is the “Code”-menu:

RStudio Code Menu

Based on the code menu the following list provides you with some selected functionalities and recommendations, which we find useful. In general, we recommend to have a look at what RStudio offers and to try out.

  • Keep RStudio up to date: RStudios functionality is constantly growing. It also adapts to be compatible with new R-versions as well as important new packages. So stay up to date, e.g., via the “Help”-menu and “Check for Updates”. You might also use the installr-package with the install.RStudio()-function (for Windows), see section Package recommendations for details.
  • Multiple lines: RStudio lets you select and edit multiple lines at once. Just try to hold Alt and select some code with your Mouse. Now the cursor spans over multiple lines. Just try it :)
  • Document outline: To give you an overview about your code, RStudio offers a document outline. There are two options to use it:
    1. In the code pane on the right you can let you show the structure of your code (or also R-markdown document). Just press Ctr+Shift+O or access it via the small “line”-icon on the top right of your code pane.
    2. Via a scrolable window on the bottom of your code pane. Just press on the text on the bottom to the right of the line:column numbers. The text always shows your actual section.
    The Coding Standard defines ways to structure your document (see also the Code Snippets compatible with RStudios document outline).

You can easily install the code snippets via the snippr-package.

First, you need to make your code snippets available with the snippr-package by editing it (only necessary once):

  1. RStudio -> Tools -> Global Options -> Code -> Tab “Editing”
  2. Click “Edit Snippets” on the bottom.
  3. Stay at the R tab and enter a new line at the end of the code:
RStudio: edt code snippets. There are code snippets available for other languages than R.



Install the package:

devtools::install_github("dgrtwo/snippr")

And now install the code snippets:

snippr::snippets_install_url("https://git.pol.joanneum.at/dvm/Rstructures/raw/branch/main/snippets/snippets.txt")

After restarting Rstudio the code snippets will be available.

4.5 R markdown

R Markdown provides an authoring framework for data science. You can use a single R Markdown file to both

  • save and execute code
  • generate high quality reports that can be shared with an audience

R Markdown documents are fully reproducible and support dozens of static and dynamic output formats. This 1-minute video provides a quick tour of what’s possible with R Markdown:

(the above text is taken from http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com/lesson-1.html)

R markdown is a very powerful tool for producing formatted documents in combination with R. It is possible to produce (among others) html, Word and PDF documents as well as websites, presentations, books or journal ready documents (see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com/formats.html). You can use R notebooks, create dashboards and even integrate interactive content. To achieve this R markdown is based on the lightweight markup language markdown.

Want to read why R markdown is great? Read Why I love R-Notebooks

4.5.1 How to get started

We can recommend three excellent starting points for working with R markdown. Choose according to your learning preference:

  1. “R Markdown Cheat Sheet”” and “R Markdown Reference Guide” (download from https://www.rstudio.com/resources/cheatsheets/)
  2. Introduction guide on the R markdown website
  3. Webinar Getting Started with R Markdown (about one hour)

4.5.2 Tips for working with R markdown

  • R markdown is fully integrated in RStudio, so working with RStudio is recommended.
  • R markdown documents are built to work as independent files. Thus, knitting an R markdown file starts with an empty environment:
    • Data and R-files have to be loaded within the R markdown file itself.
    • R markdown files use the directory they are saved in as working directory. This may be an issue when loading files or data. As working with relative paths is recommended (and setwd() is advised against), we recommend using the package rprojroot. See the packages section for more details.
  • Parameterized Reports: R Markdown documents can optionally include one or more parameters. Parameters are useful when you want to re-render the same report with distinct values for various key inputs.

4.5.3 Rendering .R files

R scripts can be rendered. Basically that means, that you can do much of what you can do with R markdown also with R scripts. RStudio offers an option to compile every R script into HTML, PDF, or MS Word format:

RStudio: compile notebook


Adding displayed text in the output, modifying the output, creating chunks, adapting the output format and so on is done through roxygen2 style comments (i.e. #').

For further information, we recommend these resources:

  • Compiling Reports from R Scripts
  • Render an R script

4.6 Testing R Code

Code testing is important and should be something that you do all the time. The R package testthat is a new testing framework which makes code testing as easy as possible. It provides several functions to describe what you expect a function to do, including catching errors, warnings as well as messages. Once defined, you can re-run the tests automatically as you change your code or tests. For a detailed description, see

  • Paper about testthat
  • “R Packages” chapter about testing
  • Book: Testing R Code

4.6.1 Code coverage

Code coverage gives you information about which part of your code is covered by unit tests and which is not. Our package recommendation covr is written by RStudio’s Jim Hester (and supported by the R Consortium). It is very simply to apply code coverage. Especially for package, it’s recommended. There are also websites like Codecov.io to help automating code coverage (especially in combination with Continuous Integration like Travis-CI).

For more information, here are some useful links:

  • covr Github page
  • Rstudio webinar about covr

4.7 Package mangagement

In general, packages are installed through the function install.packages(). This installs the newest available package version. If you want to install an older package version you can use install_version() from the devtools package. But these packages are installed globally on your computer. If you want to use packages specifically for a project or manage your packages in general, this section will provide you with some solutions.

4.7.1 Why package dependency management

R package dependencies can be frustrating. Have you ever had to use trial-and-error to figure out what R packages you need to install to make someone else’s code work–and then been left with those packages globally installed forever, because now you’re not sure whether you need them? Have you ever updated a package to get code in one of your projects to work, only to find out that the updated package makes code in another project stop working? (source: https://rstudio.github.io/packrat/)

4.7.2 Solutions

There are two main solutions (i.e. R packages) for package dependency management:

  1. packrat
    • packrat is flexible and powerful.
    • Supports non-CRAN packages (e.g. github).
    • Allows mix-and-matching package versions.
    • Requires shipping all package source.
    • Requires recipients to build packages from source.
  2. checkpoint
    • Checkpoint is simple.
    • Allows CRAN packages only.
    • Reproducibility from one script.
    • Simple for recipients to reproduce results.
    • Only allows use of CRAN packages versions that have been tested together.
    • Relies on availability of MRAN.
    • Allows only packages from one specific date (no mixing).

4.7.3 Checkpoint

Here is an example code for using checkpoint, which can be inserted in 00_init.R:

# R-version (the project is created with):
R_version <- getProjDetails("R_version") # e.g. "3.3.0"

# use checkpoint
checkpointsnapshotDate <- "2016-07-09" # (set once and do not change again)
checkpointLocation <- "~/R/win-library/" # where to store the packages
checkpoint::checkpoint(
  snapshotDate       = checkpointsnapshotDate,
  R.version          = R_version,
  checkpointLocation = checkpointLocation,
  project            = wd_rproj,
  scanForPackages     = TRUE
  )
# see the installed packages
installed.packages()[, "Package"]

# for more information see:
# https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/checkpoint/vignettes/checkpoint.html

Running into problems by using checkpoint with knitr (or R markdown) and RStudio? This article might help.

4.7.4 Packrat

packrat is not used by simply adding code to your scripts. You must initialize your project as a packrat project, which will create a folder storing all relevant information (package versions, package source, etc.). It is integrated in RStudio (see here for more information), to help you using it. For more information about setup see the walkthrough guide.

  • installr provides the function updateR() for updating R. This function…
    • Checks what is the latest R version. If the current installed R version is up-to-date, the function ends (returns FALSE).
    • If a newer version is available, the user is asked to read the NEWS of the latest R version.
    • If the user decides to update, the function will download and install the latest version.
    • Asks if all packages should be copied from the old/current to the newer R installation.
  • strict: “The goal of strict to make R behave a little more strictly, making base functions more likely to throw an error rather than returning potentially ambiguous results.
    library(strict) forces you to confront potential problems now, instead of in the future. This has both pros and cons: often you can most easily fix a potential ambiguity when you are working on the code (rather than in six months time when you’ve forgotten how it works), but it also forces you to resolve ambiguities that might never occur with your code/data.”

4.8.1 Tidyverse

tidyverse is an ecosystem of packages that use the concept of tidy data and tidy tools. The website http://tidyverse.org/ is as a good starting point. For source code of all tidyverse-packages see https://github.com/tidyverse.

  • Tidy data: “Tidy datasets are easy to manipulate, model and visualize, and have a specific structure: each variable is a column, each observation is a row, and each type of observational unit is a table.” (Hadley Wickham (2014), “Tidy data”, Journal of Statistical Software 59 (10), p.1). The concept of tidy data is an attempt to make data analysis more consistent and thus easier to program, extend, understand and work with. More information can be found in the corresponding article or the package vignette.
  • Tidy tools: Tidy tools mean “the consistent principles that unify the packages in the tidyverse. The goal of these principles is to provide a uniform interface so that tidyverse packages work together naturally, and once you’ve mastered one, you have a head start on mastering the others. There are four basic principles to a tidy API:
    1. Reuse existing data structures.
    2. Compose simple functions with the pipe.
    3. Embrace functional programming.
    4. Design for humans.
    So tidy tools extends the concept of tidy tools to programming. More information can be found in the tidy tools manifesto.

The tidyverse packages are motivated by an analysis workflow from Hadley Wickham:



The tidyverse-package itself will install the core tidyverse packages that you are likely to use in almost every analysis:

  • ggplot2, for data visualization.
  • dplyr, for data manipulation (see here for programming with dplyr).
  • tidyr, for data tidying.
  • readr, for data import.
  • purrr, for functional programming.
  • tibble, for tibbles, a modern re-imagining of data frames.
  • stringr, for strings.
  • forcats, for factors.
  • lubridate, for date/times.

Other tidyverse packages include:

  • Working with specific types of vectors:
    • hms, for times.
    • glue Glue strings to data in R. Small, fast, dependency free interpreted string literals.
  • Importing other types of data:
    • feather, for sharing with Python and other languages.
    • haven, for SPSS, SAS and Stata files.
    • httr, for web apis.
    • jsonlite for JSON.
    • readxl, for .xls and .xlsx files.
    • rvest, for web scraping.
    • xml2, for XML.
  • Modelling:
    • modelr, for modelling within a pipeline.
    • broom, for turning models into tidy data.

For a more detailed introduction see the R Views article What is tidyverse? (2017-06-08).

4.8.1.2 The pipe operator %>% (package magrittr)

Following text is taken from the magrittr-webpage

The magrittr package offers a set of operators which make your code more readable by:

  • structuring sequences of data operations left-to-right (as opposed to from the inside and out),
  • avoiding nested function calls,
  • minimizing the need for local variables and function definitions, and
  • making it easy to add steps anywhere in the sequence of operations.

The operators pipe their left-hand side values forward into expressions that appear on the right-hand side, i.e., one can replace f(x) with x %>% f(), where %>% is the (main) pipe-operator. When coupling several function calls with the pipe-operator, the benefit will become more apparent. Consider this pseudo example:

the_data <-
  read.csv('/path/to/data/file.csv') %>%
  subset(variable_a > x) %>%
  transform(variable_c = variable_a/variable_b) %>%
  head(100)

Four operations are performed to arrive at the desired data set, and they are written in a natural order: the same as the order of execution. Also, no temporary variables are needed. If yet another operation is required, it is straight-forward to add to the sequence of operations wherever it may be needed.

If you are new to magrittr, the best place to start is the pipes chapter in R for data science.

We strongly recommend to use the pipe-operator, as it makes programming a lot more readable and writable (and it’s fun 😋). For more information, please refer to the magrittr-webpage.
